# 1. For this exmaple I am using CIFAR 10 dataset
# 2. Instead of downloading it from the link I am consuming it directly from keras dataset module
# 3. Reg the model I refered to this link https://keras.io/api/applications/resnet/
# 4. I just tried Resnet101 in this example
In [4]:
# Approach summary 
#1. Downloaded the data from the keras module 
#2. Exploring the dataset and the distribution of all 10 classes
#3. Custom function to Visualize 15 images of 5 in rows from the given numpy array
#4. CNN Model to train and test.
#5. training only for 10 ephocs due to limitation of time.
#6. confusion matrix to visualize which classes are wrongly classified comparing to others 
#7. Train and test accuracy to understand the model 
#8. Same function in step 3 to explore why the images were wrongly classified 
#9. Importing resnet 101 model architecture 
#10. setting the base_model.trainable
#11 Expected to exploit images better with the pre-trained weights and transfer that learning to the new layer. 
#12. Flatten the learnings and fed to the New layer to train for the 10 outputs as in the dataset.

#observation 
#1. based on the confusion matrix many of the deers are wrongly classified as horse
#2. Visualized one wrongly classified example airplan vs automobile 
    # here we could see most of the car images in this sample are white with white or high contrast background. when comparing to the plane images these could be the reason for wrong classification.
#3. I will try adding some rotation applied to the images in the airplane to see if it can learn based on the angle.
In [6]:
#observation on the resnet model 
#1. the image size is only 32, but the resnet model is designed to have more pixels in input. 
#2. Because of the input size is 32 by the time it reaches this layer "conv4_block1_1_conv" the input size changed to (None, 2, 2, 256)
#   but if i used the input size of 200x200 by the time it reaches this layer "conv4_block1_1_conv" (None, 13, 13, 256) which has more data to work with.
#3. Instead of reshaping the input data to 200x200 and introducing more random values, I tried only with 32x32 
#4. This model didnt perform better than the basic model.
#5. based on the confusion matrix the mis-classification are high for deer and horse.

In [13]:
def plot_sample_images(images,lbls):
  plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))
  no_of_images_to_display=15
  for i in range(no_of_images_to_display):
    plt.subplot(3,5,i+1)
    plt.imshow(images[i])
    plt.xlabel(class_names[lbls[i][0]])
  plt.show()
In [14]:

In [15]:
model = models.Sequential()
model.add(layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', input_shape=(32, 32, 3)))
model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
model.add(layers.Flatten())
model.add(layers.Dense(64, activation='relu'))
model.add(layers.Dense(10))
In [16]:
model.compile(optimizer='adam',
              loss=tf.keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(from_logits=True),
              metrics=['accuracy'])

history = model.fit(train_images, train_labels, epochs=10, 
                    validation_data=(test_images, test_labels))

In [19]:
op_df = pd.DataFrame(op)
op_df["yhat"]=[np.argmax(x) for x in op]
op_df["y"] = [x[0] for x in test_labels]
op_df["yhat_lbl"] = op_df.yhat.apply(lambda x : class_names[x])
op_df["y_lbl"] = op_df.y.apply(lambda x : class_names[x])
